		<description><![CDATA[Blind The internet is a visual place. Pictures of cats in hats and dogs in bogs; most worthwhile webpages have images to comment or represent a given article. And, even if it doesn&#8217;t have an image, there are the advertisements, the videos, the related content and animated gifs. Icons that represent essential web functions. Antiquated [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Blind</p>
<p>The internet is a visual place. Pictures of cats in hats and dogs in bogs; most worthwhile webpages have images to comment or represent a given article. And, even if it doesn&#8217;t have an image, there are the advertisements, the videos, the related content and animated gifs. Icons that represent essential web functions. Antiquated assumptions on the association between the visual interpretation of an image and the content it really represents.</p>
<p>Yet with all of this I wonder at how we as content creators are servicing the market of the blind. Do you all know of resources that the blind or hard of seeing use to browse the internet?</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Imagechaos/~4/wHA8WBd6qhs" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
