		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.imagechaos.com/?p=180</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[I will be at Balticon 46 this upcoming weekend. I can be found here: NM-58 Serial Fiction 101 2 SEATS OPEN Friday, 5:00 PM, Chesapeake (50 minutes) Panelists:, Paul D. Lagasse, Gary L. Lester, Scott Sigler Moderator: Andrew Eckhart With RSS feeds, the ease of website setup, podcasts and an internet public increasingly enjoying more [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I will be at Balticon 46 this upcoming weekend. I can be found here:</p>
<p>NM-58 Serial Fiction 101 2 SEATS OPEN<br />
Friday, 5:00 PM, Chesapeake (50 minutes)<br />
Panelists:, Paul D. Lagasse, Gary L. Lester, Scott Sigler<br />
Moderator: Andrew Eckhart<br />
With RSS feeds, the ease of website setup, podcasts and an internet public increasingly<br />
enjoying more independent content, serial fiction has enjoyed a resurgence in recent years.<br />
With serial fiction readers can enjoy following the stories of their favorite characters and<br />
authors can hone their craft and gain an audience while learning how to produce on a deadline.<br />
This panel is intended to discuss the art of serial fiction, tips and tricks for this exciting type of<br />
self-publishing and the future of the platform.</p>
<p>NM-28 Social Media Promotion<br />
Saturday, 11:00 AM Derby (50 minutes)<br />
Panelists: Allison D. Duncan, Scott Hertzog, Laura Inglis, Jay Smith<br />
Moderator: Andrew Eckhart<br />
For writers, podcasters, and artists &#8211; Learning to take advantage of free or low costs internet<br />
resources to build your marketing strategy and brand.</p>
<p>Monetizing Strategies for New Media Websites<br />
Sunday, 11:00 AM, Chesapeake (50 minutes)<br />
Panelists: Allison Duncan, Andrew Eckhart, A.B. Kovacs, Paul D. Lagasse<br />
Moderator: Bryan Lincoln<br />
We&#8217;re all trying to figure out how to get people to pay us for our work, whether it&#8217;s an e-book,<br />
a podcast, an e-zine, or a blog. A panel discussion on what&#8217;s worked and what hasn&#8217;t, and why.</p>
<p>NM-52 In with the new &#8211; out with the old? Does New Media mean ignoring more traditional<br />
methods of publishing?<br />
Monday, 10:00 AM Derby (50 minutes)<br />
Panelists: J.R. Blackwell, Andrew Eckhart, Helen &#8220;Cynical Woman&#8221; Madden, Nobilis Reed<br />
Moderator: Gary L. Lester<br />
This session examines whether using only new media ideas is a good idea. There may be only so far one can go using the web as a publishing platform. Would it make sense the use a<br />
combination of traditional publishing methods and web-based marketing? Perhaps a “hybrid”<br />
approach will allow the best of both worlds.,</p>
<p>NM-48 Serialized Science Fiction: the New Pulps?<br />
Monday, 11:00 AM, Derby (50 minutes)<br />
Panelists: Andrew Eckhart, Brand Gamblin, P. G. Holyfield, Paul D. Lagasse, Gary L. Lester, D. C. Wilson<br />
Moderator: Phil Kahn<br />
The recent announcement by HiLobrow (www.hilobrow.com) that they would be serializing<br />
classic &#8220;radium age&#8221; novels on their website is perhaps the most high-profile example of an<br />
emerging trend in online publishing &#8212; serialized science fiction. Is the serial the ideal form for<br />
sub-novel length science fiction in the age of smartphones? The range of serial ventures is<br />
impressive. For example, Ray Gun Revival (www.raygunrevival.com) publishes original<br />
stories by published science fiction authors; Kat and Mouse: Guns for Hire<br />
(www.katandmouseserial.com) is a standalone serial novel; Temporal Tales<br />
(www.temporaltales.com) publishes serialized stories on Twitter; and Channel 37<br />
(www.channel-37.net) publishes novella-length stories, ongoing series, and anthology-style<br />
stories. It&#8217;s not just written science fiction that uses the serial format, either: webcomics like<br />
Spacetrawler, Valkyrie Squadron, and DRIVE, as well as audio serials such as Tales to Terrify and The Secret World Chronicle all serialize their stories too.</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Imagechaos/~4/Jb5DMviKRIE" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
